summary.text:
The user wants the map to remain useful with hundreds of pins (markers). The standard solution: marker clustering. `leaflet.markercluster` is the go-to library with React-Leaflet v5 compatibility via `react-leaflet-cluster` package... but with react-leaflet v5 + leaflet 1.9, `react-leaflet-cluster` v4 works. Let me think about what's the best approach:

Options:
1. `react-leaflet-cluster` (wrapper around leaflet.markercluster) — easy, robust. Version compatibility: react-leaflet-cluster@4.x supports react-leaflet v5? Let me recall: react-leaflet-cluster v4.0.0 added support for react-leaflet v5. Yes, v4.0.0 (2025) supports React 19 + react-leaflet v5. Good.
2. Supercluster directly — more work.

Also beyond clustering, "useful with hundreds of pins" includes:
- Clustering with counts, colored by dominant status or by count
- Clustering pins (map pins) too
- Better zoom behavior: cluster until reasonable zoom
- Maybe: only render sites matching filters (already done), "zoom to visible" fit-bounds button
- A "fit all sites" button
- Possibly spiderfy on click at max zoom

Also search/filter already limits. Performance: divIcons per marker — fine with clustering.

Let me plan:
1. Install `react-leaflet-cluster` and `leaflet.markercluster` types (@types/leaflet.markercluster).
2. Rewrite CleanupMap: wrap site markers and pin markers in MarkerClusterGroup with custom iconCreateFunction:
   - Site clusters: color by the most "urgent" status in cluster (active > planned > completed) or dominant count; size scales with count.
   - Pin clusters: amber styling.
3. Add maxClusterRadius ~60, spiderfyOnMaxZoom, showCoverageOnHover false, disableClusteringAtZoom maybe 16.
4. Custom cluster divIcon: circle with count, colored ring.
5. Add a "Fit to visible" control button overlaying map (fits bounds of filtered sites) — helps when zoomed into one cluster.
6. Cluster popup? Clicking a cluster zooms (default behavior zoomToBoundsOnClick). Good.
7. Test: generate stress-test with hundreds of markers? Could add a dev-only seed generator? Better: verify build + quick runtime smoke test. I could temporarily test by injecting random sites via console — hard without a browser. Maybe add a small script? Let me at least verify with tsx that cluster icon creation logic works? That's DOM-dependent partially (L.divIcon needs leaflet which works in node? divIcon returns object; fine in node since no DOM needed for creating the object).

Actually, a browser test would be ideal. Is there a headless browser? Probably not installed. Let me check quickly — `npx playwright` would download browsers (~100MB). Network is enabled. That might be worth it for a screenshot verification. Hmm, earlier turns just did curl smoke tests. A screenshot would be nice to verify clusters render. Let me consider: playwright install chromium ~ 170MB download. Time cost maybe 1-2 min. Worth it for visual verification of a map feature. I'll try; if it fails, fall back to build-only verification.

Also I can add a stress-test toggle: e.g., a "demo: generate 300 sites" — no, don't pollute the app. Instead, for the screenshot test, I can temporarily seed extra sites... Actually localStorage v3 is empty in fresh browser → seeds load (6 sites, 5 regions, 4 pins). Clusters won't show with 6 spread markers at zoom 12... they would cluster if close. Not great for demo.

Better idea: make the stress test reproducible — write a small Playwright script that opens the page, then uses `page.evaluate` to push 400 random sites into localStorage in the v3 format and reload, then screenshot. That validates clustering genuinely without polluting app code. 

Also markers for pins cluster too (amber).

Implementation details:

